{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}
'''Foot fetishism''', '''foot partialism''', '''foot worshipping''' or '''podophilia''', is a pronounced [[sexual interest]] in feet.<ref name=Hickey>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Hickey|first=Eric W.|title=Sex Crimes and Paraphilia|publisher= [[Pearson Education]]|year=2006|isbn=9780131703506|page=165}}</ref> It is the most common form of [[sexual fetishism]] for otherwise non-sexual objects or body parts and is more prevalent in men than women.<ref name="Dubberley2005">{{cite book|author=Emily Dubberley|title=Brief Encounters: The Women's Guide to Casual Sex|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-IH0CQAAQBAJ&pg=PT114|date=10 February 2005|publisher=Summersdale Publishers LTD - ROW|isbn=978-1-84839-313-4|page=114}}</ref><ref name="scorolli">{{cite journal|author1=Scorolli, C.|author2=Ghirlanda, S.|author3=Enquist, M.|author4=Zattoni, S.|author5=Jannini, E. A.|last-author-amp=yes|year=2007|title=Relative prevalence of different fetishes|url=http://www.nature.com/ijir/journal/v19/n4/full/3901547a.html|journal=International Journal of Impotence Research|volume=19|issue=4|pages=432–437|doi=10.1038/sj.ijir.3901547|pmid=17304204}}</ref>

==Characteristics==
[[File:Podofilija.jpg|thumb|Toe sucking and foot licking is a common way of expressing foot fetishism.]]
Foot fetishism has been defined as a pronounced sexual interest in feet. For a foot fetishist, points of attraction may include the shape and size of feet and toes (e.g. long toes, short toes, painted toenails, high arches, soles etc.), jewelry (e.g. [[toe ring]]s, [[ankle bracelet|anklets]], etc.), treatments (such as massaging, washing partner's feet or painting partner's toenails), state of dress ([[barefoot]], [[flip flops]], [[sandals]], [[high heels]], [[hosiery]], socked feet, etc.), [[foot odor]] and/or sensory interaction (e.g. rubbing the foot, tickling, smelling, kissing, biting, licking, sucking toes, [[Footjob|rubbing genitals on foot]], etc.).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kippen |first1=Cameron |title=The History of Footwear – Foot Fetish and Shoe Retifism |url=http://podiatry.curtin.edu.au/fetish.html |accessdate=10 December 2014 |via=National Library of Australia |publisher=Department of Podiatry, Curtin University |date=July 2004 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018035445/http://podiatry.curtin.edu.au/fetish.html |dead-url=yes |archivedate=18 October 2007 |df= }}</ref>

Extensions of this fetish include [[shoe fetishism|shoes]], [[socks]] and [[tickling fetish|tickling]]. [[Sigmund Freud]] considered [[foot binding]] as a form of fetishism.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hacker|first1=Authur|title=China Illustrated|date=2012|publisher=Turtle Publishing|isbn=9781462906901|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O5JyAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT252}}</ref>

==Relative frequency==
To estimate the relative frequency of fetishes, in 2006 researchers at the [[University of Bologna]] examined 381 internet discussions of fetish groups, in which at least 5,000 people had been participating. Researchers estimated the prevalences of different fetishes based on the following elements:
* (a) the number of discussion groups devoted to a particular fetish;
* (b) the number of individuals participating in the groups;
* (c) the number of messages exchanged.

It was concluded that the most common fetishes were for body parts or for objects usually associated with body parts (33% and 30% respectively). Among those people preferring body parts, feet and toes were preferred by the greatest number, with 47% of those sampled preferring them. Among those people preferring objects related to body parts, 32% were in groups related to footwear (shoes, boots, etc.).<ref name="scorolli" />

Foot fetishism is the most common form of sexual fetish related to the body.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Health/rex-ryans-foot-video-not-necessarily-unhealthy/story?id=12467617 |title=Rex Ryan's Apparent Foot Fetish not Necessarily Unhealthy – ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=23 December 2010 |accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref>

In August 2006, [[AOL]] released a database of the search terms submitted by their subscribers. In ranking only those phrases that included the word "fetish", it was found that the most common search was for feet.<ref>''AOL's Accidental Release of Search Data – The Sexmind of America.''[https://web.archive.org/web/20070221135508/http://www.aphrodisiology.com/aol-fetishes aphrodisiology.com], accessed June 2007</ref>

==Example cases==
===Health and disease===
The first surviving mention of foot fetish is by [[Bertold of Regensburg]] in 1220.<ref>Coulton, G. G. (1923) ''Life in the Middle Ages''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press</ref> Some researchers have hypothesized that foot fetishism increases as a response to epidemics of [[sexually transmitted diseases]]. In one study, conducted by Dr. A James Giannini at [[Ohio State University]], an increased interest in feet as sexual objects was observed during the great [[gonorrhea]] epidemic of twelfth-century Europe, and the [[syphilis]] epidemics of the 16th and 19th centuries in Europe.<ref>AJ Giannini et al., op. cit.</ref> In the same study, the frequency of foot-fetish depictions in [[pornographic literature]] was measured over a 30-year interval. An exponential increase was noted during the period of the current [[AIDS epidemic]]. In these cases, sexual footplay was viewed as a [[safe sex]] alternative. However, the researchers noted that these epidemics overlapped periods of relative female emancipation.<ref>{{cite journal| last1=Giannini|first1=AJ|last2=Colapietro|first2=G|last3=Slaby|first3=AE|last4=Melemis|first4=SM|last5=Bowman|first5=RK|title= Sexualization of the female foot as a response to sexually transmitted epidemics: a preliminary study|journal=Psychological Reports|volume=83|issue=2|pages=491–8|year=1998|pmid=9819924|doi=10.2466/pr0.83.6.491-498}}</ref> Sexual focus on female feet was also hypothesized to have been a reflection of a more dominant posture of the woman in sexual-social relations.

===Causes===
{{See also|Sexual fetishism}}
Foot fetishism is caused by the feet and the genitals occupying adjacent areas of the [[Postcentral gyrus|somatosensory cortex]], possibly entailing some neural crosstalk between the two.<ref>Kringelbach, Morten. ''Bodily Illusions''. [http://www.kringelbach.dk/Preprint_Beagle_BodilyIllusions.html kringelbach.dk] last accessed Sept 2006.</ref> Ramachandran has noted amputees reporting orgasms in their feet.<ref name="Ramachandran">{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Blakeslee|first=Sandra|title=[[Phantoms in the Brain: Probing the Mysteries of the Human Mind]]|publisher= [[HarperCollins]]|year=1999|isbn=9780688172176}}</ref>

[[Desmond Morris]] considered foot fetishism the result of [[Imprinting (psychology)|mal-imprinting]] at an early age, the tactile pressure of a foot/shoe being important in this.<ref>Desmond Morris, ''The Naked Ape Trilogy'' (1994) p. 279-80</ref>

Freud's reading of foot-fetishism also involved early imprinting; but he considered the smell of feet significant in this, as well as the foot as penis-symbol/surrogate ([[castration complex]], especially when encountered while voyeuristic exploring the female body from below).<ref>Sigmund Freud, ''On Sexuality'' (PFL 7) p. 68n</ref>  [[Otto Fenichel]] similarly saw castration fear as significant in foot fetishism, citing a future fetishist who as an adolescent said to himself "You must remember this throughout life – that girls, too, have legs", to protect himself from the fear.<ref>Quoted in O. Fenichel, ''The Psychoanalytic Theory of Neurosis'' (1946) p. 327</ref> Where fear of the (castrated) female body is too great, desire is felt not for shoes on female feet but for women's shoes alone, without women.<ref>O. Fenichel, ''The Psychoanalytic Theory of Neurosis'' (1946) p. 343</ref>

